The '''Croatia national football team''' ({{langx|hr|Hrvatska nogometna reprezentacija}}) represents [[Croatia]] in men's international [[Association football|football]] matches. It is governed by the [[Croatian Football Federation]] (HNS), the governing body for [[football in Croatia]]. It is a member of [[UEFA]] in Europe and [[FIFA]] in global competition. The team's colours reference two national symbols: the [[Croatian checkerboard]] and the [[Flag of Croatia|country's tricolour]]. They are colloquially known as the {{lang|hr|Vatreni}} (Blazers) and the {{lang|hr|Kockasti}} (Checkered Ones). 

Since 2000, the {{lang|hr|Vatreni}} have qualified for every major tournament except [[UEFA Euro 2000]] and the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]]. At the [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]], Croatia has finished second once ([[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018]]) and third on two occasions ([[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998]], [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022]]), securing three World Cup medals. [[Davor Šuker]] won the [[FIFA World Cup awards|Golden Shoe]] and the [[FIFA World Cup awards|Silver Ball]] in 1998, while [[Luka Modrić]] won the [[FIFA World Cup awards|Golden Ball]] in 2018 and the [[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Ball|Bronze Ball]] in 2022. The team has reached the quarter-finals of the [[UEFA European Championship]] twice ([[UEFA Euro 1996|1996]], [[UEFA Euro 2008|2008]]). They finished second in the [[UEFA Nations League]] in [[2022–23 UEFA Nations League|2023]]. As of March 2026, Croatia maintains an [[World Football Elo Ratings|Elo Rating]] of 1,944 with an all-time high of 2,012 recorded in 2023. 

Upon its admission into FIFA in 1994 ranked 125th, they ascended to third place with their debut [[Croatia at the 1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 World Cup campaign]]. This marked the [[Croatia national football team#FIFA ranking history|fastest, most volatile ascension]] in FIFA ranking history, making them the youngest team to ever reach a Top 10 place in the [[FIFA Men's World Ranking|World Ranking]]. Croatia is the second-smallest country by population (after [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]]) and land mass (after the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]]) to reach a [[List of FIFA World Cup finals|World Cup final]]. At the World Cup, Croatia [[FIFA World Cup records and statistics|hold records]] for most [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]] played (4) and won (4) and most [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalties]] saved in a shoot-out (3), among other [[Croatia national football team records and statistics|team records]]. They were named [[FIFA Men's World Ranking#Best Mover of the Year|FIFA Best Mover of the Year]] in 1994 and 1998, thus becoming the first national team to win the award twice.

==History==
===Official formation===
Various unofficial sides delineated the early history of Croatian football as Croatia was [[Croatian affairs in the Kingdom of Yugoslavia|not an independent entity]] until the late 20th century.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Rogić |first=Marijan |title=Hrvatsko nogometno predstavništvo 1940. - 2008. |publisher=Gipa |year=2008 |isbn=978-953-95297-1-8 |location=Zagreb |language=hr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Sengupta |first=Arjun |date=2022-12-10 |title=The improbable rise of the Croatian football team |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/explained/explained-sports/croatia-brazil-fifa-world-cup-luka-modric-8316331/ |access-date=2022-12-16 |website=The Indian Express |language=en}}</ref> Hugo Kinert first managed an unofficial side that played international matches in 1918–19.<ref name="yugoslavtimes">{{cite web |url=http://www.uvijekvjerni.com/reprezentacija/povijest/ |publisher=Uvijek Vjerni |title=Hrvatska nogometna reprezentacija kroz povijest |access-date=14 August 2008 |language=hr |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120216063940/http://www.uvijekvjerni.com/reprezentacija/povijest |archive-date=16 February 2012 }} ''[[Talk:Croatia national football team#Hrvatska nogometna reprezentacija kroz povijest|Translation]]''</ref> In 1940, [[Jozo Jakopić]] led the national side representing the [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] [[Banovina of Croatia]] in four friendly matches.<ref name="croatiamatches">{{cite web|url=https://www.rsssf.org/tablesk/kroa-intres.html|title=Croatia International matches |author1=Igor Kramarsic |author2=Bojan Puric |author3=Roberto Di Maggio |website=Rec. Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation|access-date=14 July 2008}}</ref> Following the 1941 [[Axis powers|Axis]] [[invasion of Yugoslavia]], [[Nazi Germany|Germany]] and [[Fascist Italy (1922–1943)|Italy]] [[Government of the Independent State of Croatia|took control]] of Croatia, forming the [[Independent State of Croatia]] and installing [[Rudolf Hitrec]] as an unofficial manager for two years.<ref name=":4">{{Cite web |author1=Michael Colborne |author2=Una Hajdari |title=In Croatia, Sympathizers Are Welcome to Join the Party |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2018/07/31/in-croatia-nazi-sympathizers-are-welcome-to-join-the-party-thompson-ustashe-fascism/ |access-date=2022-12-15 |website=Foreign Policy |language=en-US}}</ref> The side played 15 friendly matches from its re-activation in [[FIFA]] in 1941 until the [[End of World War II in Europe|end of World War II]].<ref name="fedohist">{{cite web |url=http://croatiasoccer.blog.hr/2007/09/1623284234/povijest-hrvatskog-nogometnog-saveza.html |publisher=H-R |title=Povijest Hrvatskog Nogometnog Saveza |date=25 September 2007 |access-date=19 August 2008 |language=hr }} ''[[Talk:Croatia national football team#Povijest Hrvatskog Nogometnog Saveza|Translation]]''</ref><ref name="croathistory">{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/associations/association=cro/goalprogramme/index.html|title=Goal Programme&nbsp;– Croatian Football Federation&nbsp;– 2006|date=17 July 2008|publisher=FIFA|access-date=4 September 2008|archive-date=4 September 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080904011838/http://www.fifa.com/associations/association=cro/goalprogramme/index.html}}</ref> In 1945, Croatia returned to [[FPR Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]] as the [[Socialist Republic of Croatia|People's Republic of Croatia]] with sides active until 1956.<ref name="fedohist" /><ref name="croatiamatches" /> During the nation's pre-independence, [[Croats|Croat]] footballers played for [[Yugoslavia at the Summer Olympics]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rsssf.org/tableso/ol1956f.html |publisher=Rec. Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation |author=Esamie, Thomas |title=Games of the XVI. Olympiad |access-date=8 August 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922131126/http://rsssf.com/tableso/ol1956f.html |archive-date=22 September 2008 }}</ref> the [[Yugoslavia at the FIFA World Cup|FIFA World Cup]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=76/teams/team=43975.html|publisher=Fédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA.com)|title=1990 FIFA World Cup squads&nbsp;– Yugoslavia|access-date=26 August 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080908002806/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition%3D76/teams/team%3D43975.html|archive-date=8 September 2008}}</ref> and the [[Yugoslavia at the UEFA European Championship|UEFA European Championship]] from 1956 to 1990.<ref name="debutfinish" /><ref>Ramet 2005, p. 171</ref>

Croatia debuted their modern [[Croatian checkerboard|checkered]] jersey against the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] on 17 October 1990, [[1990 Croatia v United States football match|winning 2–1]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rsssf.org/miscellaneous/asanovic-intl.html |publisher=Rec. Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation |title=Aljosa Asanovic&nbsp;– International appearances |access-date=20 July 2008 }}</ref><ref name="nacional.hr">{{cite magazine |author1=Mario Duspara |author2=Tanja Simić |date=20 February 2006 |title=Hrvatske kocke opet modni hit |trans-title=Croatian chequy are fashionable again |url=http://www.nacional.hr/articles/view/23275/ |magazine=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]] |language=hr |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120728160544/http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/23275/hrvatske-kocke-opet-modni-hit |archive-date=28 July 2012 |access-date=30 June 2012}}</ref> Caretaker manager [[Dražan Jerković]], led the ''[[de facto]]'' national side before their formal re-admission into FIFA on 3 July 1992,<ref>{{cite web |title=Sve o sportu |url=http://www.sveosportu.com/hrvatskareprezentacijanogomet/Hrvatskareprezentacija.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716171205/http://www.sveosportu.com/hrvatskareprezentacijanogomet/Hrvatskareprezentacija.htm |archive-date=16 July 2011 |access-date=16 August 2011 |publisher=Sve o sportu}}</ref> winning two more friendly games against [[Romania national football team|Romania]] in December 1990 and [[Slovenia national football team|Slovenia]] in June 1991.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.balkantimes.com/cocoon/setimes/xhtml/bg/features/setimes/features/2002/10/021008-SVETLA-002 |publisher=Southeast European times |title=Croatia Marks Independence Day for First Time |access-date=21 July 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rsssf.org/tablesk/kroa-intl9095.html |publisher=Rec. Sport Soccer Statistics Foundation |title=Croatia&nbsp;– International matches 1990–1995 |access-date=18 July 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080612091143/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesk/kroa-intl9095.html |archive-date=12 June 2008 }}</ref> [[Stanko Poklepović]] took over team management and led them on an exhibition tour in their debut against [[Australia men's national soccer team|Australia]], before he was succeeded by [[Vlatko Marković]] in April 1993.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Vlatko Marković biography |url=https://hns-cff.hr/news/4389/vlatko-markovic-biography/ |access-date=2022-12-16 |website=hns-cff.hr |language=hr}}</ref> Croatia gained admission into [[UEFA]] in June 1993, three months after [[1994 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|qualification]] for the [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994 World Cup]] started, missing their window to enter the competition.<ref name="Morse">{{Cite web |last=Morse |first=Ben |date=2022-12-13 |title=From bloody Balkan war to World Cup heavyweight: the making of Croatia as a soccer nation |url=https://www.cnn.com/2022/12/12/football/croatia-profile-argentina-2022-world-cup-spt-intl/index.html |access-date=2022-12-14 |website=CNN |language=en}}</ref> After winning a match against [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]] in June 1993, Marković was succeeded by [[Miroslav Blažević]] in March 1994.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Goff |first=Steven |date=1998-07-06 |title=AFTER CHAOS, CROATIA UNITES IN A PASSIONATE JOURNEY |language=en-US |newspaper=Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/sports/1998/07/06/after-chaos-croatia-unites-in-a-passionate-journey/31ed55b1-5381-4084-90d6-00948ba9409f/ |access-date=2022-12-16 |issn=0190-8286}}</ref>

