[[File:The 1998 Third Place Certificate for Croatia.jpg|thumb|Croatia's third-place certificate and bronze medal for the [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 World Cup]]]]
After the [[independence of Croatia]], the newly formed Croatia entered the [[FIFA Men's World Ranking|FIFA World Rankings]] in 125th place in March 1994.<ref name="tourneyhist">{{cite web |title=Fantasy Euro2008 |url=http://twg.fantasyeuro2008.sbs.com.au/stats.aspx?page=team&id=313 |access-date=3 August 2008 |publisher=The World Game}} {{dead link|date=June 2010|bot=DASHBot}}</ref><ref name="croatiaranks">{{cite web |title=Croatia&nbsp;– FIFA World Rankings |url=https://www.fifa.com/associations/association=cro/ranking/gender=m/index.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180925230226/https://www.fifa.com/associations/association=cro/ranking/gender=m/index.html |archive-date=25 September 2018 |access-date=11 August 2008 |publisher=Fédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA.com)}}</ref> Blažević launched Croatia's [[UEFA Euro 1996 qualifying Group 4|qualifying campaign]] for [[UEFA Euro 1996|Euro 1996]] with a 2–0 win over [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]] on 4 September 1994 and a 1–0 away loss to Ukraine on 1 June 1995, their first competitive win and loss.<ref name="croatiamatches" /> After finishing first in qualifying, the team halved their spot in the World Ranking, ascending to number 62, winning FIFA's 1994 [[FIFA Men's World Ranking|Best Mover of the Year]] in December 1994.<ref>{{cite web |title=Best Mover of the Year |url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/awards/gala/bestmover.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081026144822/http://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/awards/gala/bestmover.html |archive-date=26 October 2008 |access-date=11 December 2008 |publisher=FIFA}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=1996 European Championship&nbsp;– Qualifying |url=http://www.thefa.com/EURO2004/History/Postings/2003/01/37017.htm |archive-url=https://archive.today/20050211182457/http://www.thefa.com/EURO2004/History/Postings/2003/01/37017.htm |archive-date=11 February 2005 |access-date=10 August 2008 |publisher=The Football Association}}</ref> In the Euro 1996 [[UEFA Euro 1996 Group D|group stage]], [[Goran Vlaović]] scored the team's first goal at a tournament, a late strike to win 1–0 against [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/history/news/0254-0d7bc21c63d9-f27016e59e05-1000--croatia-contemplate-turkey-task/ |work=European Championships archive |publisher=Union of European Football Associations (UEFA.com)|title=Croatia contemplate Turkey task |date=4 January 2008 |access-date=31 December 2012 }}</ref> Croatia then beat [[UEFA Euro 1992 Final|reigning champions]] [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] 3–0,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.euro2008.uefa.com/history/season=1996/round=227/match=52515/index.html |work=European Championships archive |publisher=Union of European Football Associations (UEFA.com) |title=Šuker stars as Danes downed |date=16 June 1996 |access-date=10 August 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080422120939/http://en.euro2008.uefa.com/history/season%3D1996/round%3D227/match%3D52515/index.html |archive-date=22 April 2008 }}</ref> later losing to [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]] by the same scoreline.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/portugal-take-advantage-of-slack-croatia-1337981.html |work=[[The Independent]]|author=Jon Culley |title=Portugal take advantage of slack Croatia |date=20 June 1996 |access-date=31 December 2012 }}</ref> The team advanced to the [[UEFA Euro 1996 knockout stage|knockout stage]] and were beaten in the [[UEFA Euro 1996 knockout stage#Germany vs Croatia|quarter-finals]] 1–2 by [[Germany national football team|Germany]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.euro2008.uefa.com/history/season=1996/round=223/match=52913/index.html |work=European Championships archive |publisher=Union of European Football Associations (UEFA.com) |title=Germany overcome ten-man Croatia |date=23 June 1996 |access-date=10 August 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080505143403/http://en.euro2008.uefa.com/history/season%3D1996/round%3D223/match%3D52913/index.html |archive-date=5 May 2008 }}</ref> Croatia's [[UEFA Euro 2000 qualifying Group 8|qualifying campaign]] from 1998 to 1999 for [[UEFA Euro 2000|Euro 2000]] was unsuccessful as they finished third in their group behind [[Serbia and Montenegro national football team|FR Yugoslavia]] and the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]].<ref>{{cite news |date=10 October 1999 |title=Sport: Football Euro 2000 qualifying group tables |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC News) |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/sport/football/191195.stm |access-date=23 July 2008}}</ref> Both fixtures against Yugoslavia ended in draws which prevented Croatia from qualifying by one point.<ref name="Sukerman2">{{cite web |author=Islamović, Elvir |date=1 April 2008 |title=Suker: a man with the Midas touch |url=http://www.euro2008.uefa.com/news/kind=2/newsid=638977.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080523012306/http://www.euro2008.uefa.com/news/kind%3D2/newsid%3D638977.html |archive-date=23 May 2008 |access-date=22 July 2008 |work=European Championship archive |publisher=Union of European Football Association (UEFA.com)}}</ref>

Croatia began their [[1998 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group 1|qualification campaign]] for the [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 World Cup]] with an aggregate victory against Ukraine in the two-legged [[1998 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA second round|playoff]]. In the [[1998 FIFA World Cup Group H|group stage]], Croatia beat both [[Jamaica national football team|Jamaica]] and [[Japan national football team|Japan]], later losing to [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] to advance with them to the [[1998 FIFA World Cup knockout stage|knockout stage]]. A 1–0 victory over Romania moved the Croatians to the [[1998 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Germany vs Croatia|quarter-finals]] against Germany.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/ranking/lastranking/gender=m/fullranking.html#confederation=0&rank=50 |publisher=Fédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA.com) |title=FIFA/Coca-Cola World Ranking |date=20 May 1998 |access-date=10 December 2008 |archive-date=8 April 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120408200223/http://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/ranking/lastranking/gender=m/fullranking.html?#confederation=0&rank=50 }}</ref> Croatia beat the Germans 3–0 with goals from [[Robert Jarni]], Goran Vlaović and [[Davor Šuker]], all after [[Christian Wörns]] had been sent off.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Longman |first=Jere |date=1998-07-05 |title=WORLD CUP '98; Croatia Stuns Germany With the Aid Of a Red Card |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/07/05/sports/world-cup-98-croatia-stuns-germany-with-the-aid-of-a-red-card.html |access-date=2022-12-16 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> They advanced to their first [[1998 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#France vs Croatia|semi-final]] against hosts [[France national football team|France]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Blum |first=Ronald |date=2018-07-12 |title=France-Croatia World Cup final invokes memories of infamous dive in 1998 |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/soccer/world-cup/france-croatia-world-cup-final-invokes-memories-of-infamous-dive-in-1998/article_1fad7689-b4f9-54a6-8f01-e99340bf3ef0.html |access-date=2024-07-06 |website=Toronto Star |language=en}}</ref> After a goalless first-half, Croatia led after [[Aljoša Asanović]] pushed past [[Zinedine Zidane]] to cross a ball downfield to Šuker who scored after a one-on-one with goalkeeper [[Fabien Barthez]].<ref name="theguardian.com">{{Cite web |date=2022-06-12 |title=Tragedy and triumph: the remarkable tale of Croatia's first football steps |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2022/jun/12/tragedy-and-triumph-the-remarkable-tale-of-croatias-first-football-steps |access-date=2022-12-11 |website=The Guardian |language=en}}</ref> France's defender [[Lilian Thuram]] equalized quickly after, and scored another goal later in the game to beat Croatia 2–1.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Aarons |first=Ed |date=2018-07-15 |title=The day Lilian Thuram turned into a goalscorer supreme for France |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2018/jul/15/lilian-thuram-goalscorer-supreme-france-1998-world-cup-croatia |access-date=2024-07-06 |work=The Observer |language=en-GB |issn=0029-7712}}</ref> In the [[1998 FIFA World Cup knockout stage#Third place play-off|third place match]], Croatia prevailed against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] 2–1 to secure bronze and claim their first World Cup medal.<ref name="Morse"/> Šuker won the [[FIFA World Cup Golden Boot|Golden Shoe]] for scoring the most goals in the World Cup: six goals in seven games.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=1013/overview.html |publisher=Fédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA.com) |title=Zidane lights the blue-touch paper for France |access-date=11 August 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130804134815/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition%3D1013/overview.html |archive-date=4 August 2013 }}</ref> The Croatians' performance during the late-1990s propelled them to rank third place in the [[FIFA Men's World Ranking|FIFA World Ranking]] in January 1999.<ref name="croatiaranks" /><ref name="debutfinish">{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E06E0DD123EF935A35754C0A96E958260 |work=The New York Times|author=Longman, Jere| title= World Cup '98; Croatia and Its Fortunate Sons |date=6 July 1998 |access-date=10 August 2008}}</ref> The team of the 1990s was dubbed the "[[golden generation]]"{{efn|A portion of this squad (Jarni, [[Igor Štimac|Štimac]], [[Zvonimir Boban|Boban]], [[Robert Prosinečki|Prosinečki]] and Šuker) previously won the [[1987 FIFA World Youth Championship]] with the [[Yugoslavia national under-20 football team|Yugoslavia under-20 team]].<ref name="theguardian.com" />}} for their contributions to Croatia's ascension in international football.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-19045559.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140610214543/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-19045559.html |archive-date=10 June 2014 |journal=[[The Sunday Herald]]|author=Campbell, Alan |title=The Golden Generation beginning to show their age |date=2 September 2001 |access-date=31 December 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/history/news/0254-0d7bf9b32b1d-c3db0f06d46c-1000--pletikosa-inspired-by-croatia-s-past/ |work=European Championships archive |publisher=Union of European Football Associations (UEFA.com)|title=Pletikosa inspired by Croatia's past |date=9 June 2008 |access-date=31 December 2012 }}</ref>

===Jozić, Barić and Kranjčar period (2000–2006)===
[[File:CroaciavsSuica2004.JPG|thumb|Fans during [[UEFA Euro 2004|Euro 2004]] in Portugal]]
Croatia started their [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group 6|qualifying campaign]] for the [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 World Cup]] with draws against [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] and [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] prompting Blažević's resignation as head coach in October 2000.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Hughes |first1=Rob |last2=Tribune |first2=International Herald |date=2000-10-25 |title=Sign of Troubled Times as 2 Coaches Depart Under a Cloud |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/10/25/sports/IHT-sign-of-troubled-times-as-2-coaches-depart-under-a-cloud.html |access-date=2022-12-16 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> His successor, [[Mirko Jozić]], pushed the team through the rest of qualifiers undefeated. In the [[2002 FIFA World Cup Group G|group stage]], Croatia narrowly lost to [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] before beating [[Italy national football team|Italy]] 2–1 and sustaining a 1–0 loss to [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=4395/preliminaries/preliminary=3835/index.html |publisher=Fédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA.com) |title=2002 FIFA World Cup Korea/Japan Preliminaries |access-date=10 August 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081112061454/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition%3D4395/preliminaries/preliminary%3D3835/index.html |archive-date=12 November 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport3/worldcup2002/hi/matches_wallchart/italy_v_croatia/newsid_1925000/1925415.stm |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC Sport) |title=Croatia punish Italy|date=8 June 2002 |access-date=10 August 2008 }}</ref> The team was eliminated by one point,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport3/worldcup2002/hi/matches_wallchart/ecuador_v_croatia/default.stm |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC Sport) |title=Ecuador end Croatia hopes |date=13 June 2002 |access-date=10 August 2008 }}</ref> leading to the resignation of Jozić and succession of [[Otto Barić]] in July 2002, their first manager born outside of [[Southeast Europe]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport3/worldcup2002/hi/team_pages/croatia/newsid_2048000/2048514.stm|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC Sport) |title=Jozić to step down |date=16 June 2002 |access-date=31 August 2008 }}</ref> During Barić's tenure, most of the remaining players from the "golden generation" squad were gradually replaced by younger players over the course of [[UEFA Euro 2004 qualifying Group 8|qualifying]] for [[UEFA Euro 2004|Euro 2004]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/euro_2004/croatia/players_to_watch/3569075.stm |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC Sport) |title=Barić leads Croatian charge |date=26 May 2004 |access-date=31 August 2008 }}</ref> Croatia qualified in a [[UEFA Euro 2004 qualifying play-offs|playoff]] victory against Slovenia, winning 2–1 on aggregate after [[Dado Pršo]]'s decisive late goal in the second leg.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/2899301.stm |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC Sport) |title=Euro 2004 Qualifying Group Eight |date=11 October 2004 |access-date=31 August 2008 }}</ref> The team was eliminated at the [[UEFA Euro 2004 Group B|group stage]] after drawing 0–0 with Switzerland and 2–2 with France, and losing 2–4 to [[England national football team|England]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/euro_2004/3787501.stm |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC News) |title=England 4–2 Croatia |date= 21 June 2004|access-date=23 July 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/euro_2004/3813635.stm |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC News) |title=Croatia 2–2 France |date=17 June 2004 |access-date=23 July 2008 }}</ref> Barić departed after his two-year contract expired in June 2004.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/euro_2004/croatia/3707619.stm |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC News) |title=Barić to step down |date=27 May 2004 |access-date=31 August 2008 }}</ref> Prior to launching the team's [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group 8|qualification]] for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]], [[Zlatko Kranjčar]] succeed in July 2004.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2021-03-01 |title=Zlatko Kranjcar, former Croatia national team coach, dies |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/sports/zlatko-kranjcar-former-croatia-national-team-coach-dies/ |access-date=2022-12-17 |website=The Seattle Times |language=en-US}}</ref> Croatia qualified undefeated, finishing top of the group ahead of [[Sweden men's national football team|Sweden]] and [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2004/soccer/07/13/east.europe/index.html |work=CNNSports Illustrated |title=Former striker Kranjčar hired to lead Croatia to World Cup |date=13 July 2004 |access-date=22 July 2008 |archive-date=25 October 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025130521/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2004/soccer/07/13/east.europe/index.html }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/preliminaries/preliminary=8071/index.html |publisher=Fédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA.com) |title=2006 World Cup qualifying standings |access-date=22 July 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140112182108/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/preliminaries/preliminary%3D8071/index.html |archive-date=12 January 2014 }}</ref> In the [[2006 FIFA World Cup Group F|group stage]], Croatia lost their opening match against [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] and drew 0–0 with Japan after [[Darijo Srna]] missed a first-half [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/results/matches/match=97410011/report.html |publisher=Fédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA.com) |title=2006 FIFA World Cup&nbsp;– Brazil vs Croatia match report |access-date=11 August 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080710084320/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/results/matches/match%3D97410011/report.html |archive-date=10 July 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/results/matches/match=97410028/report.html |publisher=Fédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA.com) |title=2006 FIFA World Cup&nbsp;– Croatia vs Japan match report |access-date=11 August 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080729042235/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/germany2006/results/matches/match%3D97410028/report.html |archive-date=29 July 2008 }}</ref> A 2–2 draw with Australia in which three players were sent off confirmed Croatia's elimination.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4853428.stm |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC Sport) | title=Croatia 2–2 Australia |date=22 June 2006 |access-date=19 October 2008 }}</ref>

===Bilić period (2006–2012)===
[[File:FIFA World Cup 2006 - BRA vs CRO.jpg|thumb|Croatia vs. [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] at the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]]]]
In July 2006, Kranjčar was replaced by [[Slaven Bilić]], who introduced newer, younger players into the squad and concluded [[UEFA Euro 2008 qualifying Group E|qualifying]] undefeated.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-16706585.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140611020252/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-16706585.html |archive-date=11 June 2014 |journal=[[The Sunday Herald]] |title=Fear Factor: Despite his brutish look, Croatia manager Slaven Bilić has charisma and passion, just do not make him mad|author=Grant, Michael|date=7 June 2008 |access-date=31 December 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/5214026.stm |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC Sport) |title=Bilić appointed new Croatia coach |date=25 July 2006 |access-date=20 August 2008 }}</ref> His first match resulted in a 2–0 victory against [[2006 FIFA World Cup final|reigning world champions]] Italy during an international friendly.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/slaven-bilic-encouraging-my-players-is-my-way-of-doing-things-846997.html |work=The Independent |title=Slaven Bilic: Encouraging my players is my way of doing things|date=14 June 2008 |access-date=3 September 2008 | location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rediff.com/sports/2006/aug/17euro.htm |publisher=Rediff News |author=Phillips, Mitch |title=Croatia beat Italy 2–0 |date=17 August 2006 |access-date=20 August 2008 }}</ref> Croatia lost once to [[North Macedonia national football team|Macedonia]] and defeated England twice, resulting in their failure to qualify for the first time since [[UEFA Euro 1984 qualifying Group 3|1984]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=197471&&cc=3436 |work=ESPNSoccernet |title=Macedonia 2–0 Croatia: Croats qualify |date=17 November 2007 |access-date=7 October 2008 |archive-date=19 October 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019204546/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=197471&&cc=3436 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/croatia-england-face-off-again-in-world-cup-qualifying-1.676179 |agency=Associated Press |publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation (CBC Sports)|title=Croatia, England face off again in World Cup qualifying |date=25 November 2007 |access-date=24 July 2008 }}</ref> [[Eduardo da Silva]], the team's top goalscorer during qualifying, suffered an injury while playing for his club, [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]], leading to a reshuffle in the [[UEFA Euro 2008 squads#Croatia|finals squad]] with less experienced players.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Harris |first=Nick |date=2008-03-27 |title=Scotland 1 Croatia 1: Scotland show spirit to kick-start Burley era |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/scotland-1-croatia-1-scotland-show-spirit-to-kickstart-burley-era-with-welcome-draw-801312.html |access-date=2022-12-14 |website=The Independent |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Islamović, Elvir |date=5 May 2008 |title=Bilić names squad for EURO assault |url=http://www.euro2008.uefa.com/news/kind=1/newsid=692102.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080526202029/http://www.euro2008.uefa.com/news/kind%3D1/newsid%3D692102.html |archive-date=26 May 2008 |access-date=31 August 2008 |work=European Championships archive |publisher=Union of European Football Associations (UEFA.com)}}</ref> Croatia finished their play in [[UEFA Euro 2008 Group B|Group B]] undefeated, with a 1–0 win over co-hosts [[Austria national football team|Austria]], a 2–1 victory against Germany, and a 1–0 win over [[Poland national football team|Poland]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Cheese |first=Caroline |date=2007-11-21 |title=Euro 2008 qualifying as it happened |language=en-GB |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/7103968.stm |access-date=2022-12-17}}</ref> The team achieved the maximum group stage points possible (nine) for the first time in [[Croatia at the UEFA European Championship|their Euros history]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/7310062.stm |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC Sport)|author=Moffat, Colin | title=Scotland 1–1 Croatia |date=26 March 2008|access-date=1 September 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/match?id=238245&cc=3436&league=FIFA.FRIENDLY |work=ESPNSoccernet |title=Croatia 1–0 Moldova |access-date=1 September 2008 |archive-date=19 October 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019204601/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/match?id=238245&cc=3436&league=FIFA.FRIENDLY }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.euro2008.uefa.com/tournament/matches/match=300701/index.html |work=European Championships archive |publisher=Union of European Football Associations (UEFA.com) |author=Haylett, Trevor |title=Klasnić completes Croatian clean sweep |date=16 June 2008 |access-date=21 July 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080501160817/http://www.euro2008.uefa.com/tournament/matches/match%3D300701/index.html |archive-date=1 May 2008 }}</ref> [[Niko Kovač]] and [[Dario Šimić]] served as captains during the group and knockout stages, respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2008/06/19/sports/EU-SPT-SOC-Euro-2008-Croatia-Kovac.php |work=International Herald Tribune |title=Croatia captain Niko Kovac to retire from national team after Euro 2008 |date=19 June 2008 |access-date=28 July 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/15062008/58/euro-2008-bilic-field-reserves-against-poland.html |publisher=Eurosport |title=Bilić to field reserves against Poland |date=15 June 2008 |access-date=28 July 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080618220558/http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/15062008/58/euro-2008-bilic-field-reserves-against-poland.html |archive-date=18 June 2008 }}</ref> Croatia pushed Turkey to a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]] in the [[UEFA Euro 2008 knockout stage#Croatia vs Turkey|quarter-finals]], in which the Turkish side prevailed in an upset where [[Luka Modrić]], [[Mladen Petrić]], and [[Ivan Rakitić]] all missed their penalties.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ashdown |first=John |date=2008-06-20 |title=Football: Euro 2008 quarter-final: Croatia v Turkey -as it happened |language=en-GB |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/jun/20/croatiaturkey.euro2008quarterfinal |access-date=2022-12-14 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2008/06/20/sports/EU-SPT-SOC-Euro-2008-Croatia-Bilic.php |work=International Herald Tribune |title= Bilić on wrong end of upset as Croatia fluff the penalty shootout in Euro 2008 quarterfinals |date=21 June 2008 |access-date=24 July 2008 }}</ref> Croatia set [[UEFA European Championship records and statistics|multiple Euro records]]: fewest goals conceded (2), fewest games lost (0),{{efn|Under the rules of Association football and the official European Championship tournament regulations, a loss inflicted via a penalty shootout does not count as a defeat but rather a tie which needed a final process to determine the team which advances per the [[Laws of the Game (association football)|Laws of the Game]].}} and earliest goal scored.<ref name="amidcont">{{cite news |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/euro_2008/croatia/7467523.stm |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC Sport) |title=Bilić came close to quitting job |date=21 June 2008 |access-date=3 September 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/euro_2008/7363048.stm |publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC Sport) |author=Hughes, Ian| title=Austria 0–1 Croatia |date=8 June 2008|access-date=26 August 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/21062008/58/euro-2008-comeback-kings-turkey.html?page=2&order=date |publisher=Eurosport |author=Maher, Reda |title=Euro 2008&nbsp;– Comeback kings Turkey do it again |date=21 June 2008 |access-date=6 September 2008 }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>

Bilić renewed his contract in April 2008,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/euro2008/story/0,23063,13950_3497423,00.html |publisher=SkySports.com |title=Bilić agrees new Croatia deal |date=30 April 2008 |access-date=23 July 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090111205151/http://www.skysports.com/football/euro2008/story/0%2C23063%2C13950_3497423%2C00.html |archive-date=11 January 2009 }}</ref> before the [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA Group 6|qualifying campaign]] for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 World Cup]]. Croatia won 3–0 against [[Kazakhstan national football team|Kazakhstan]], before enduring a 4–1 loss to England at [[Stadion Maksimir]], their first home loss in 14 years.<ref name="englandmt">{{cite news|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/internationals/7602774.stm|title=Croatia 1–4 England|author=Stevenson, Jonathan|date=11 September 2008|access-date=11 September 2008|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC Sport)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/newsid=652649.html#england+croatia+topping+bill |publisher=Fédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA.com) |title=England-Croatia topping the bill |date=5 December 2007 |access-date=24 July 2008 |archive-date=9 August 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080809045655/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/newsid=652649.html#england+croatia+topping+bill }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=236375&&cc=3436 |work=ESPNSoccernet |title=Croatia 3–0 Kazakhstan: Croats cruise |date=6 September 2008 |access-date=11 September 2008 |archive-date=27 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110427033414/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=236375&&cc=3436 }}</ref> The team drew 0–0 with Ukraine and beat [[Andorra national football team|Andorra]] twice, drawing again with Ukraine and beating [[Belarus national football team|Belarus]] twice. In the final stretch of the qualifiers, England delivered Croatia's then-heaviest loss, a 5–1 scoreline, at [[Wembley Stadium]].<ref name="Reuters">{{Cite news |agency=Reuters |date=2009-09-09 |title=England Routs Croatia and Qualifies for World Cup |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/10/sports/soccer/10worldcup.html |access-date=2022-12-12 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The team had several injuries during qualifying and were ultimately eliminated on points, as Ukraine defeated both England and Andorra to advance in the group.<ref>{{Cite web |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=2009-10-16 |title=Slaven Bilic will not resign after Croatia fail to make 2010 World Cup |url=http://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/oct/16/slaven-bilic-croatia-world-cup |access-date=2022-12-11 |website=The Guardian |language=en}}</ref>

Croatia was a candidate to [[UEFA Euro 2012 bids|co-host Euro 2012]] with [[Hungarian Football Federation|Hungary]] which would have resulted in automatic qualification for both countries; UEFA ultimately selected [[Polish Football Association|Poland]] and [[Ukrainian Association of Football|Ukraine]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2007-04-12 |title=Peterjon Cresswell: why Euro 2012 could go east |url=http://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/apr/12/europeanfootball.sport |access-date=2022-12-14 |website=The Guardian |language=en}}</ref> The Croatians began their [[UEFA Euro 2012 qualifying Group F|qualifying campaign]] for [[UEFA Euro 2012|Euro 2012]] with a 3–0 win over [[Latvia national football team|Latvia]], a goalless draw with [[Greece national football team|Greece]], and a 2–1 win against [[Israel national football team|Israel]]. In the [[UEFA Euro 2012 qualifying play-offs|qualifying playoff]] against Turkey, the team won 3–0 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro2012/standings/index.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100206144152/http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro2012/standings/index.html |archive-date=6 February 2010 |publisher= 1998–2011 UEFA |title=UEFA Qualifying Round |date=28 September 2011 |access-date=27 September 2011 }}</ref> They were [[UEFA Euro 2012 Group C|grouped]] with the Republic of Ireland, Italy and [[UEFA Euro 2008 Final|defending champions]] [[Spain national football team|Spain]], opening with a 3–1 victory over the Irish.<ref>{{cite web |date=4 October 2010 |title=Match Schedule |url=https://www.uefa.com/MultimediaFiles/Download/competitions/Draws/01/72/67/72/1726772_DOWNLOAD.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111209124311/https://www.uefa.com/MultimediaFiles/Download/competitions/Draws/01/72/67/72/1726772_DOWNLOAD.pdf |archive-date=9 December 2011 |work=[[UEFA]] |publisher=Union of European Football Associations}}</ref> Croatia drew with Italy 1–1 in a match marred by [[Concerns and controversies related to UEFA Euro 2012#Other incidents|disruptive fans]] and controversial refereeing from English official [[Howard Webb]].<ref name=robsmyth>{{Cite news |last=Smyth |first=Rob |date=2012-06-14 |title=Euro 2012: Italy v Croatia – as it happened |language=en-GB |work=The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/jun/14/euro-2012-italy-croatia-live-mbm |access-date=2022-12-13 |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Spain knocked out the side in a 0–1 loss, which, along with 1–1 rematch with Italy, had Croatia eliminated.<ref name=robsmyth/> Bilić retired before [[UEFA Euro 2012|Euro 2012]], with the Croatians continuously ranked among the top ten teams in the world during his tenure – 2007 to 2012.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Croatia Ranking History |url=https://www.fifa.com/fifa-world-ranking/CRO |access-date=2022-12-12 |website=FIFA |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2012-06-19 |title=Euro 2012: Slaven Bilic leaves Croatia a proud but disappointed man |author=Aleksandar Holiga |url=http://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2012/jun/19/euro-2012-slaven-bilic-croatia |access-date=2022-12-10 |website=The Guardian |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vecernji.hr/sport/vijesti/ponosni-smo-sto-smo-imali-bas-ovakvog-slavena-bilica-clanak-422740 |publisher=Jutarnji List |title=Ponosni smo sto smo imali bas ovakvog Slavena Bilica |date=20 June 2012 |access-date=21 June 2012 }}</ref>

===Štimac, Kovač and Čačić period (2012–2017)===
[[File:Brazil and Croatia match at the FIFA World Cup 2014-06-12 (10).jpg|thumb|Croatia vs. Brazil at the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]]]]
Succeeding Bilić, former player [[Igor Štimac]] was appointed manager. At the same time, Davor Šuker assumed the presidency of the Croatian Football Federation in 2012 after the death of Vlatko Marković.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gol.dnevnik.hr/clanak/nogomet/reprezentacije/suker-predsjednik-stimac-izbornik-a-vrbanovic-maminjov-osigurac |title=Šuker novi predsjednik HNS-a: Ujedinio sam nogometnu Hrvatsku! |last=Medo |first=Ivica |date=5 July 2012 |access-date=21 July 2014 |language=hr |publisher=Gol.hr }}{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vecernji.hr/domaci-nogomet/igor-stimac-novi-izbornik-hrvatske-nogometne-reprezentacije-427742 |title=Igor Štimac novi izbornik hrvatske nogometne reprezentacije! |language=hr |date=5 July 2012 |access-date=21 July 2014}}</ref> A year in, Štimac was replaced by former captain Niko Kovač.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hrsport.net/vijesti/467243/nogomet-reprezentacija/igor-stimac-razrijesen-duznosti-izbornika-reprezentaciju-preuzima-niko-kovac |title=Igor Štimac razriješen dužnosti izbornika, reprezentaciju preuzima Niko Kovač! |last=Korać |first=Branimir |date=16 October 2013 |access-date=21 July 2014 |language=hr |work=Sportnet.hr |archive-date=7 January 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107214436/http://www.hrsport.net/vijesti/467243/nogomet-reprezentacija/igor-stimac-razrijesen-duznosti-izbornika-reprezentaciju-preuzima-niko-kovac/ }}</ref> Kovač led the team to a 2–0 aggregate victory over [[Iceland national football team|Iceland]] in the [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification – UEFA second round|qualifying playoffs]] for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]] with both goals coming in the home leg in [[Zagreb]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/round=258394/match=300261016/report.html|title=2014 FIFA World Cup Brazil: Croatia-Iceland - Report |publisher=FIFA|access-date=1 July 2018|archive-date=10 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190610144107/https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/matches/round=258394/match=300261016/report.html}}</ref> In the [[2014 FIFA World Cup Group A|group stage]], Croatia opened their campaign with a 3–1 loss to hosts Brazil. The match garnered media attention for [[List of 2014 FIFA World Cup controversies#Brazil vs Croatia|controversial refereeing]] from [[Yuichi Nishimura]] which was scrutinized for a number of decisions.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/25285029|title=Brazil 3 Croatia 1|work=BBC Sport|date=12 June 2014|access-date=19 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Dunbar |first=Graham |title=Brazil-Croatia referee Yuichi Nishimura ignites officiating controversy |url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/sports/2014/06/12/brazil-croatia-referee-yuishi-nichimura-ignites-officiating-controversy/MGQhAeiLjxlQ6DXI3u0M0M/story.html |access-date=2022-12-10 |website=The Boston Globe  |language=en-US}}</ref> In their second match, Croatia won 4–0 against [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]] then lost 3–1 to Mexico, finishing third in the group and missing the [[2014 FIFA World Cup knockout stage|knockout stage]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/25285326|title= Croatia 1 Mexico 3|date=23 June 2014|work=BBC Sport|access-date=24 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/worldcup/news/newsid=2119094.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140628231818/http://www.uefa.com/worldcup/news/newsid=2119094.html|archive-date=28 June 2014|title=Croatia's World Cup highs and lows|author=Elvir Islamović|date=24 June 2014|publisher=UEFA|access-date=27 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/25285162|title=Cameroon 0 Croatia 4|work=BBC Sport|date=18 June 2014|access-date=19 June 2014}}</ref>
[[File:Croatie - Portugal 2016.jpg|thumb|Croatia vs. Portugal at [[UEFA Euro 2016|Euro 2016]]]]
During the [[UEFA Euro 2016 qualifying Group H|qualifying campaign]] of [[UEFA Euro 2016|Euro 2016]], Croatia drew with [[Azerbaijan national football team|Azerbaijan]] and lost to [[Norway national football team|Norway]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/european-qualifiers/news/0253-0d7f7f20f59e-fca9f8b24173-1000--italy-cling-on-to-hold-croatia/|title=Italy cling on to hold Croatia|author=Ben Gladwell|date=16 November 2014|publisher=UEFA|access-date=29 November 2014}}</ref> leading to Kovač's replacement with [[Ante Čačić]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://hr.n1info.com/a70714/Sport-Klub/Nogomet/Katastrofa-Hrvatske-u-Oslu-Norveska-pobijedila-2-0.html|title=Hrvatska potučena u Oslu u najvažnijoj utakmici kvalifikacija|work=N1 HR|access-date=1 July 2018|language=hr|archive-date=2 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702011504/http://hr.n1info.com/a70714/Sport-Klub/Nogomet/Katastrofa-Hrvatske-u-Oslu-Norveska-pobijedila-2-0.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hns-cff.hr/en/news/12208/hns-terminates-niko-kovacs-contract/|title=HNS terminates Niko Kovač's contract|date=9 September 2015|work=[[Croatian Football Federation]]|access-date=15 October 2015}}</ref> The team broke their record for most goals scored in a match with a friendly 10–0 win over [[San Marino national football team|San Marino]] in June 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/sports/soccer/2016/06/04/croatia-beats-san-marino-by-record-10-0-in-euro-2016-warmup/85412824/ |title=Croatia beats San Marino by record 10–0 in Euro 2016 warmup|date=4 June 2016|access-date=4 June 2016|work=USA Today|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> They topped the [[UEFA Euro 2016 Group D|group stage]] of that year's Euros, advancing with [[UEFA Euro 2012 Final|defending champions]] Spain.<ref>{{cite news |date=13 October 2015 |title=Malta 0 Croatia 1 |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/34524236 |access-date=14 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=21 September 2015 |title=Ante Čačić takes over Croatia reins |url=http://hns-cff.hr/en/news/12255/ante-cacic-takes-over-croatia-reins/ |access-date=15 October 2015 |work=[[Croatian Football Federation]]}}</ref> Croatia prevailed over Turkey 1–0 with a long-range volley goal from Luka Modrić,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/36454287|title=Turkey 0–1 Croatia|date=12 June 2016|work=BBC Sport|access-date=1 July 2018}}</ref> before drawing 2–2 against the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://sport.hrt.hr/339815/euro2016/stream-euro-2016-ceska-hrvatska|title=[VIDEO] Remi Hrvatske i Češke nakon nereda na tribinama|work=Hrvatska radiotelevizija|access-date=1 July 2018|archive-date=2 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702012449/http://sport.hrt.hr/339815/euro2016/stream-euro-2016-ceska-hrvatska}}</ref> In the latter match, Croatia led with goals from [[Ivan Perišić]] and Ivan Rakitić, while opposing Czech striker [[Milan Škoda]] and a last-minute penalty from [[Tomáš Necid]] drew the match.<ref name=":3">{{Cite web |last=Hunter |first=Andy |date=2016-06-17 |title=Czech Republic comeback marred by Croatia flare and fan incidents |url=http://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/jun/17/croatia-czech-republic-euro-2016-match-report |access-date=2022-12-15 |website=The Guardian |language=en}}</ref> There was severe crowd trouble<ref name=":3" /> and on-field flares in the game's last minutes with a steward injured by a stray firework.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/36496116|title=Czech Republic 2–2 Croatia|date=17 June 2016|work=BBC Sport|access-date=1 July 2018}}</ref> Croatia then defeated Spain 2–1, confirming the Spaniards' first defeat at a Euro finals match since [[UEFA Euro 2004 Group A#Spain vs Portugal|2004]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/36524210|title=Croatia 2–1 Spain|date=21 June 2016|work=BBC Sport|access-date=1 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/croatia-vs-spain/353085|title=Croatia 2–1 Spain: Ivan Perišić hands Croatia dramatic win to top Group D|work=Sky Sports|access-date=1 July 2018}}</ref> The Croatians were tipped as one of the tournament favourites<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenationalnews.com/sport/croatia-have-become-euro-2016-favourites-after-beating-spain-says-nikola-kalinic-1.224419|title=Croatia have become Euro 2016 favourites after beating Spain, says Nikola Kalinic|work=The National|access-date=1 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2016/06/21/football/euro-2016-spain-croatia-czech-republic-turkey-group-d/index.html|title=Euro 2016: Croatia stuns reigning champion Spain to top Group D|first=Matias |last=Grez|publisher=CNN|access-date=1 July 2018}}</ref> as they entered the [[UEFA Euro 2016 knockout stage|knockout stage]] with Portugal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/36535365|title=Hungary 3–3 Portugal|date=22 June 2016|work=BBC Sport|access-date=1 July 2018}}</ref> The Portuguese prevailed 1–0 with [[Ricardo Quaresma]]'s winning goal in the 117th minute after Perišić hit the post with a header in the previous attack.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/36566064|title=Croatia 0–1 Portugal|date=25 June 2016|work=BBC Sport|access-date=1 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Glendenning |first=Barry |date=2016-06-25 |title=Croatia 0-1 Portugal: Euro 2016 – as it happened |url=http://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2016/jun/25/croatia-v-portugal-euro-2016-live |access-date=2022-12-15 |website=The Guardian |language=en}}</ref> Following the campaign, Darijo Srna announced his retirement and the succession of Modrić as team captain in August 2016.<ref>{{cite web |title=Luka Modrić, the new captain: "I'm so proud"|url=http://hns-cff.hr/en/news/14953/luka-modric-the-new-captain-im-so-proud/|work=Croatian Football Federation|date=29 August 2016|access-date=29 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Trifunović, Boris|date=9 August 2016|access-date=9 August 2016|work=24sata|language=hr|title=Srna je dobio nasljednika: Luka Modrić novi kapetan Hrvatske|trans-title=Srna has his successor: Modrić is Croatia's new captain|url=http://www.24sata.hr/sport/srna-je-dobio-nasljednika-luka-modric-novi-kapetan-hrvatske-486432}}</ref>

