===Supporters===
[[File:ITA-CRO Euro 2012 (3).JPG|left|thumb|Croatia supporters at [[UEFA Euro 2012|Euro 2012]], featuring the [[Croatian checkerboard|national checkerboard]]]]
The team has developed an extensive fan base since the 1990s.<ref>Foster 2004, p. 52</ref> Following their debut run at the [[1998 FIFA World Cup|1998 World Cup]], there was a rise in domestic and global attention for the side. Political scientist [[Alex J. Bellamy]] observed in 2003 that the national team became a symbol of statehood in Croatia after [[Independence of Croatia|their independence]] through the [[Cultural diplomacy|cultural export]] of football.<ref>Bellamy, Alex. 2003. ''The Formation of Croatian National Identity: A Centuries-old Dream'', Manchester University Press, pg. 116</ref> The government's influence on team affairs eased substantially after the death of President [[Franjo Tuđman]] in 1999. All matches are followed and televised throughout the country, particularly during major tournaments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrt.hr/1793/satellite-broadcasting/broadcasting-hrt-programmes-via-satellite-for-australia-and-new-zealand|title=HRT Broadcasts via Satellite to Australia and New Zealand|date=20 May 2008|publisher=Hrvatska radiotelevizija|access-date=24 November 2008|archive-date=13 December 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221213193515/https://www.hrt.hr/1793/satellite-broadcasting/broadcasting-hrt-programmes-via-satellite-for-australia-and-new-zealand}}</ref> In November 2022, the [[Ministry of Science and Education (Croatia)|Ministry of Science and Education]] issued guidance to let school children watch matches during the school day as long coursework is made up later.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Đukić |first=Ružica |date=2022-11-18 |title=Ako mogu u Saboru, što ne bi i u školi - Fuchs odobrio gledanje nogometa i učenicima |url=https://danas.hr/video/hrvatska/ako-mogu-u-saboru-sto-ne-bi-i-u-skoli-fuch-odobrio-gledanje-nogomet-i-ucenicima-342cbb14-6774-11ed-878c-2a7d7571aa87 |access-date=2022-12-11 |website=danas.hr |language=hr-HR}}</ref> Following the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018 World Cup]], the Croatian Cabinet attended ministerial meetings in team jerseys,<ref>{{Cite web |date=2018-07-13 |title=Croatia's cabinet members wore team jerseys to celebrate their entry into FIFA World Cup 2018 final |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/trending/trending-globally/croatias-cabinet-wore-jerseys-to-celebrate-entering-fifa-world-cup-2018-final-5258144/ |access-date=2022-12-11 |website=The Indian Express |language=en}}</ref> and during the [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022 World Cup]], Prime Minister [[Andrej Plenković]] delivered a hurried speech "[lasting] only 37 seconds" at the [[Union for the Mediterranean|Euro-Mediterranean Summit]] to catch the quarter-finals.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Trujillo |first=Marco |date=2022-12-09 |title=At summit, southern EU leaders watch World Cup on Croatian PM's mobile |language=en |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/world/europe/beaming-croatian-pm-celebrates-world-cup-stunner-eumed-summit-2022-12-09/ |access-date=2022-12-11}}</ref>

The Croatian Football Federation endorses an official fan club for the team, known as {{lang|hr|Uvijek Vjerni|italics=no}} ("Always Faithful").<ref>{{cite web |title=About the club |url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=hr&u=http://www.uvijekvjerni.com/o_klubu/o-klubu/&prev=/search%3Fq%3DUvijek%2BVjerni%26hl%3Den%26sa%3DG |access-date=4 January 2009}}</ref> A part of the team's support consists of fans of [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]] and [[HNK Hajduk Split|Hajduk Split]], the two largest clubs in Croatia's top domestic football league, the {{lang|hr|[[Croatian Football League|Hrvatska nogometna liga]]}} (HNL).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gfk.hr/press/nogomet.htm|title=Za koji hrvatski nogometni klub navijate?|date=18 May 2005|publisher=Growth from Knowledge (GFK Hrvatska)|language=hr|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080430100239/http://www.gfk.hr/press/nogomet.htm|archive-date=30 April 2008|access-date=19 August 2008}} ''[[Talk:Croatia national football team#Za koji hrvatski nogometni klub navijate?|Translation]]''</ref> Both sets of fans—[[Bad Blue Boys]] from [[Zagreb]] and [[Torcida Split|Torcida]] from [[Split, Croatia|Split]]—have been associated with [[hooliganism]] due to their [[Ultras|ultra-style support]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.com.mt/news.asp?newsitemid=73131|title=Incident brings back memories of Malta-Croatia match: Seven Hajduk fans arrested|author=Brincat, Henry|publisher=The Malta Independent|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430202522/http://www.independent.com.mt/news.asp?newsitemid=73131|archive-date=30 April 2011|access-date=7 August 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/may/31/sport.comment2|title=Is hooliganism inevitable at this World Cup? |author=Brimson, Dougie |author2=Miles, Kevin|date=31 May 2006|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=4 September 2008|location=London}}</ref> Regional support for the team also comes from [[Croats of Bosnia and Herzegovina]], particularly from fans of domestic clubs [[HŠK Zrinjski Mostar|Zrinjski Mostar]] and [[NK Široki Brijeg|Široki Brijeg]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/observer/osm/story/0,,1123137,00.html|title=Football, blood and war|date=18 January 2004|work=The Observer|access-date=26 August 2008|location=London}}</ref> The [[Croatian diaspora|diaspora of Croatians]] across the [[Croatian Americans|United States]] (for ex. "[[Los Angeles]] Vatreni" fan group<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sport.hrt.hr/hrvatski-nogomet/hrvati-na-ulicama-orlanda-vjeruju-u-pobjedu-nad-brazilom-12647989|title=Hrvati na ulicama Orlanda vjeruju u pobjedu nad Brazilom|trans-title=Croats on the streets of Orlando believe in victory over Brazil|website=vijesti.hrt.hr|publisher=Croatian Radiotelevision (HRT)|date=31 March 2026|language=hr|quote=Bobby, član skupine navijača Los Angeles Vatreni, uvjeren je da će Brazil krenuti po pobjedu pa će biti odlična utakmica.}}</ref>), [[Croatian Canadians|Canada]], [[Croatian Australians|Australia]], and South America contribute to the majority of the side's international support.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.news.com.au/sport/football/world-cup/forget-its-coming-home-you-shouldnt-be-supporting-england/news-story/164e1df3f2948f9c72a7c17690f47794|title=Forget 'It's coming home', you shouldn't be supporting England|author=Murray, Oliver|work=News.com.au|access-date=22 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/back-to-the-future-croatia-s-presence-in-australian-football|title=Back to the future - Croatia's presence in Australian football|author=Gorman, Joe|work=The World Game |publisher=SBS|access-date=22 July 2018}}</ref> It is customary among supporters to include an inscription of their city of origin onto the Croatian flag. Fans also coordinate their vocal support and orchestrate chants during matches. One section may shout "{{lang|hr|[[U boj, u boj]]}}" ("To battle, to battle") with another responding "{{lang|hr|Za narod svoj}}" ("For our people").<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://direktno.hr/eu-i-svijet/dijaspora/video-slavlje-ulicama-kanade-bjezite-ljudi-bjezite-iz-grada-128107/|title=VIDEO Slavlje na ulicama Kanade: Bježite ljudi, bježite iz grada|date=12 July 2018|work=direktno.hr|access-date=12 July 2018|language=hr|archive-date=6 April 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230406011557/https://direktno.hr/eu-i-svijet/dijaspora/video-slavlje-ulicama-kanade-bjezite-ljudi-bjezite-iz-grada-128107/}}</ref> In addition to chants, the team regularly have songs dedicated to them, such as [[Slaven Bilić]]'s "{{lang|hr|Vatreno ludilo|italics=no}}" (''Fiery Madness'') which topped Croatian music charts during [[UEFA Euro 2008|Euro 2008]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/news/newsid=745497.html|title=Bilić has Croatia rocking|date=18 April 2008|publisher=Fédération Internationale de Football Association (FIFA.com)|access-date=15 July 2008|archive-date=6 December 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081206170129/http://www.fifa.com/confederationscup/news/newsid=745497.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://goal.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/06/19/rock-on-slaven-bilic/|title=Rock on Slaven Bilic|author=Marcus, Jeffrey|date=19 June 2008|work=The New York Times|access-date=14 August 2008}}</ref>
[[File:Croatianwelcoming.jpg|thumb|Smoke from supporters' pyrotechnics in [[Ban Jelačić Square]], 2018]]
The disruptive behaviour of supporters during matches, particularly those exhibiting [[Ultras|ultra-style fandom]], has complicated national team affairs. [[Hooliganism]], rioting, vandalism, littering, violence, use of [[Flare|pyrotechnics]] and discriminatory political expression have led to sanctions both domestically and internationally. The team has been emblematic of [[Croatian nationalism]] since the early-1990s [[independence of Croatia]].<ref name=":4" /><ref>{{Cite web |last=Matic |first=Srecko |date=19 June 2024 |title=Are Croatian hooligans really right-wing extremists? |url=https://www.dw.com/en/euro-2024-does-croatia-have-a-problem-with-right-wing-extremist-hooligans/a-69411580 |access-date=19 June 2024 |website=Deutsche Welle |language=en}}</ref> The football federation, government, and players have made material efforts to prevent unwanted incidents to avoid damage to the perception of the team and Croatian people.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Holiga |first=Aleksandar |date=2014-11-17 |title=Croatia fans' act of terrorism in Italy was a planned cry for attention |url=http://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2014/nov/17/croatia-fans-terrorism-italy-planned-cry-attention |access-date=2022-12-15 |website=The Guardian |language=en}}</ref> This has included banning their own fans from certain games.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2015-08-21 |title=Croatia bans own fans for Euro qualifiers over racism fears |language=en |work=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/uk-soccer-euro-croatia-fans-idUKKCN0QQ1ZT20150821 |access-date=2022-12-11}}</ref> The behaviour of fans has led to penalties and fines for the national team imposed by FIFA and UEFA.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2012/06/20/sport/football/euro-2012-croatia-racism-new/index.html?hpt=hp_bn2|title=Croatia faces fresh Euro 2012 racism probe|date=20 June 2012|publisher=CNN|access-date=20 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.javno.com/en/sports/clanak.php?id=157833|title=Police Clash with Croatian Football Fans|author=Eder, Alan|date=20 June 2008|publisher=Javno|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081207065015/http://www.javno.com/en/sports/clanak.php?id=157833|archive-date=7 December 2008|access-date=8 September 2008}}</ref> The Croatian Football Federation has been assessed significant disciplinary fines and penalties since the early 2000s.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2008-09-25 |title=Football: Croatia get away with £15,000 fine for abuse of Heskey |url=http://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/sep/26/worldcup2010qualifiers.englandfootballteam |access-date=2022-12-10 |website=The Guardian |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2012-06-19 |title=Euro 2012: Croatia fined £65,000 for racist abuse of fans |url=http://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/jun/19/euro-2012-croatia-fined-racism |access-date=2022-12-11 |website=The Guardian |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Millar |first=Colin |title=Euro 2024 teams hit with more than €1.2m in fines by UEFA |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5608382/2024/07/01/euro-2024-teams-fines-uefa/ |access-date=2024-07-06 |work=The New York Times |date=3 July 2024 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In addition to monetary fines, the team has faced tournament point deductions and have had their supporters banned.<ref>{{Cite news |last=McNulty |first=Phil |date=October 12, 2018 |title=England hit woodwork twice in Croatia draw |language=en-GB |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/45755081 |access-date=2022-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last1=Burt |first1=Jason |last2=Field |first2=Pippa |date=2018-10-12 |title=England fail to exact World Cup revenge over Croatia as Marcus Rashford misses chances in empty stadium |language=en-GB |work=The Telegraph |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2018/10/12/croatia-vs-england-uefa-nations-league-live-score-latest-updates/ |access-date=2022-12-17 |issn=0307-1235}}</ref> There have also been multiple acts of protest against the national team, in response to allegations of corruption.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com.au/european-championship/74/blog/post/2896570/why-are-croatian-fans-disrupting-their-countrys-matches-at-euro-2016?src=com|title=Why did Croatian fans use flares to disrupt their team's Euro matches?|last=Marcotti|first=Gabriele|date=18 June 2016|publisher=[[ESPN]]|access-date=24 July 2018}}</ref>

===Charity===
To advance the team's charitable efforts, manager [[Slaven Bilić]] established the ''Vatreno Srce'' (Fiery Heart) Foundation in 2010.<ref name="vatrenosrce">{{cite web |last=Janković |first=Ivan |date=14 November 2018 |title=Vatreno srce ponovo ujedinilo Hrvatsku oko reprezentacije: Djeci prikupljena značajna sredstva |url=https://www.tportal.hr/sport/clanak/vatreno-srce-ponovo-ujedinilo-hrvatsku-oko-nogometa-za-djecu-vise-od-40-tisuca-poziva-20181113 |access-date=24 March 2020 |website=Tportal.hr |language=hr}}</ref> The primary cause of the foundation is helping children.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Rupnik |first=Borna |date=13 May 2010 |title=Vatreno srce hrvatske reprezentacije |url=https://sportnet.rtl.hr/vijesti/397105/nogomet-reprezentacija/vatreno-srce-hrvatske-reprezentacije/ |access-date=24 March 2020 |website=rtl.hr |language=hr |archive-date=29 October 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211029064949/https://sportnet.rtl.hr/vijesti/397105/nogomet-reprezentacija/vatreno-srce-hrvatske-reprezentacije/ }}</ref> As of 2012, the foundation made fifty donations of 1,200,000 [[Croatian kuna|HRK]] to various children's organizations.<ref name="aukcija">{{cite web |date=17 December 2012 |title=Humanitarna zaklada "Vatreno srce" prikupila 500.000 kuna |url=https://sport.hrt.hr/193948/humanitarna-zaklada-vatreno-srce-prikupila-500000-kuna |access-date=24 March 2020 |website=HRT Sport |language=hr}}</ref> In December 2012, the foundation made 500,000 HRK on an auction of [[Niko Kranjčar]]'s shirt and [[Lionel Messi]]'s shirt that was signed by all [[FC Barcelona]] players. The auction was organised in the [[Esplanade Zagreb Hotel]] and attended by President of Croatia [[Ivo Josipović]].<ref name="aukcija" /> In November 2018, the players gathered in [[Westin Hotels & Resorts|The Westin Hotel]] in Zagreb to answer fans' phonecalls, the proceeds of which were donated to the Vatreno Srce Foundation. In 2018, the foundation financed Children's Hospital Zagreb and ''Korak u Život'' (A Step Into Life), a charity that helps young children raised in orphanages transition into higher education.<ref name="vatrenosrce" /><ref>{{Cite web |last=Bahtijarević |first=Nika |date=19 February 2019 |title=Raising funds for children |url=https://www.uefa.com/news-media/news/024e-0f8e6854b258-795657354e8f-1000--raising-funds-for-children/ |access-date=24 March 2020 |website=UEFA}}</ref> In November 2019, more than 500,000 [[Croatian kuna|HRK]] was collected in another call event that were then directed to Children's Hospital Kantrida.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Premec |first=Tina |date=11 November 2019 |title=FOTO: ZAKLADA 'VATRENO SRCE' TIJEKOM DONATORSKE VEČERI PRIKUPILA VIŠE OD POLA MILIJUNA KUNA ZA DJECU Vatreni su bili najveće zvijezde na svečanosti |language=hr |work=Jutarnji list |url=https://www.jutarnji.hr/spektakli/domace-zvijezde/foto-zaklada-vatreno-srce-tijekom-donatorske-veceri-prikupila-vise-od-pola-milijuna-kuna-za-djecu-vatreni-su-bili-najvece-zvijezde-na-svecanosti/9603262/}}</ref> In March 2020, the players collectively donated 4.2 million [[Croatian kuna|HRK]] to combat the [[COVID-19 pandemic in Croatia|COVID-19 pandemic]] and for repair of damage caused by the [[2020 Zagreb earthquake]].<ref>{{cite web |author=A. Ha. |date=24 March 2020 |title=Hrvatski nogometaši skupili više od četiri milijuna kuna za borbu protiv koronavirusa |url=https://www.index.hr/mobile/clanak.aspx?category=sport&id=2168496 |website=Index.hr |language=hr}}</ref> Members of national team visit and help children with special needs and their education institutions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.croatiaweek.com/croatian-national-teams-gesture-of-support-for-firefighters-and-special-needs-community-in-osijek/|title=Croatian national team's gesture of support for firefighters and special needs community in Osijek|website=croatiaweek.com|publisher=Croatia Week|date=13 October 2023|access-date=14 October 2023}}</ref>

==Stadiums==
The national team has played in thirteen stadiums around the country. The majority of Croatia's home matches take place at [[Stadion Maksimir]] in [[Zagreb]], the country's [[List of football stadiums in Croatia|largest football stadium]], which is also the home-ground of local football club [[GNK Dinamo Zagreb|Dinamo Zagreb]].<ref name="maksimirren">{{citation |url=http://www.panstadia.com/vol7/74-022.htm |publisher=Panstadia |volume=7 |number=4 |author=McIntyre, Katie |title=Architecture & Design&nbsp;– Maksimir Stadium |access-date=7 August 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100113111022/http://www.panstadia.com/vol7/74-022.htm |archive-date=13 January 2010 }}</ref> The Croatian Football Federation previously agreed on extensive plans with the government to renovate the stadium and increase its forty-thousand seating capacity, the proposal was eventually rejected by [[List of mayors of Zagreb|Mayor of Zagreb]] [[Milan Bandić]] in 2008 due to construction costs.<ref name="maksimirren"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=88735 |publisher=Javno |title=Maksimir Stadium&nbsp;– World's Most Expensive |date=11 October 2007 |access-date=7 July 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081207063118/http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=88735 |archive-date=7 December 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=88773|publisher=Javno|title=Mayor: I Will Not Build Stadium at That Cost|date=11 October 2007|access-date=12 September 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081207064944/http://www.javno.com/en/croatia/clanak.php?id=88773|archive-date=7 December 2008}}</ref> Home matches are occasionally played at other, smaller venues around the country. [[Stadion Poljud]] in [[Split, Croatia|Split]] has hosted some qualifying fixtures since 1995. Between 1995 and 2011, Croatia never won a competitive match at Poljud, which the local media dubbed ''Poljudsko prokletsvo'' ("the Poljud curse").<ref>{{cite web| url=http://arhiva.net.hr/sport/page/2008/02/06/0466006.html| publisher=Net.hr| title=Nastavljeno poljudsko prokletstvo| date=6 February 2008| access-date=21 November 2010| language=hr| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111009062756/http://arhiva.net.hr/sport/page/2008/02/06/0466006.html| archive-date=9 October 2011}} ''[[Talk:Croatia national football team#Nastavljeno poljudsko prokletstvo|Translation]]''</ref> Qualifying fixtures have also been played at [[Stadion Kantrida]] in [[Rijeka]] along with [[Gradski Vrt Stadium|Stadion Gradski Vrt]] in Osijek and [[Stadion Varteks]] in [[Varaždin]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://slobodnadalmacija.hr/Nogomet/tabid/84/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/256786/Default.aspx| newspaper=Slobodna Dalmacija| title=Vatreni poručili HNS-u: Ne želimo više igrati "manje utakmice" u Maksimiru| date=10 September 2014| access-date=27 November 2014| language=hr}}</ref>
