Surpassing [[Robert Jarni]]'s previous record of 81 appearances,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/sportsNews/idUKL053798320080605|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090111132332/http://uk.reuters.com/article/sportsNews/idUKL053798320080605|archive-date=11 January 2009|title=Croatia's Dario Simic Eyes 100th Cap|author=Milosavljevic, Zoran|date=5 June 2008|access-date=25 August 2008|work=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sportnet.hr/Vijest.aspx?ID=365317|title=Šimić završio sa stotkom|author=Pacak, Tomislav|date=15 September 2008|work=Sportnet.hr|language=hr|access-date=25 August 2008}} ''[[Talk:Croatia national football team#Šimić završio sa stotkom|Translation]]''</ref> [[Dario Šimić]] was the first player to reach 100 appearances, doing so before his retirement in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=cro/news/newsid=1512193.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100815001056/http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=cro/news/newsid=1512193.html|archive-date=15 August 2010|title=Šimić ends playing career|date=11 August 2010|publisher=Union of European Football Associations |website=uefa.com|access-date=11 August 2010}}</ref> Darijo Srna, Josip Šimunić and Stipe Pletikosa collectively reached their 100th cap in February 2013.<ref>{{cite news |title=Darijo Srna scored on 100th appearance for Croatia in 4-0 win over South Korea |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/13950/8475986/darijo-srna-scored-on-100th-appearance-for-croatia-in-4-0-win-over-south-korea |access-date=16 December 2022 |website=Sky Sports}}</ref> Srna was the most capped player from 2016 to 2021, with 134 appearances.<ref>{{cite news |title=Darijo Srna: A record holder, a captain, an icon |url=https://hns-cff.hr/en/news/14856/darijo-srna-a-record-holder-a-captain-an-icon/ |access-date=16 December 2022 |website=hns-cff.hr|publisher=Hrvatski nogometni savez (Croatian Football Federation)}}</ref> He was surpassed by Luka Modrić in 2021.<ref>{{cite news |title=Croatia win as Modric sets caps record |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/56552534 |access-date=2022-12-16}}</ref>

The youngest player to play for Croatia is [[Alen Halilović]] (aged {{Age in years, months and days |month1 = 6 |day1 = 18 |year1 = 1996 |month2 = 6 |day2 = 10 | year2 = 2013 }}),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hns-cff.hr/players/110408/alen-halilovic/|title=Alen Halilović player profile|publisher=Hrvatski nogometni savez (Croatian Football Federation)|access-date=6 February 2018|language=hr}}</ref> while the oldest is Luka Modrić ({{Age in years, months and days |month2 = 6 |day2 = 2 |year2 = 2026 |month1 = 9 |day1 = 9 | year1 = 1985 }}).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hrnogomet.com/reprezentacija/najstarijiIgraci.php?sortOrder=desc&sortBy=5&stranica=1&lang=hr|title=Statistike hrvatskog nogometa|trans-title=Croatian football's statistics|publisher=HR Nogomet|access-date=6 February 2018|language=hr}}</ref>

